item.title: Rhino Scripting?
item.dc:creator: @lawl lawl
item.description:
@lawl wrote:

[quote=“BAsh, post:17, topic:292206”]I built an ASM based code transformer (think: not remover / shift simplifier / etc) with javascript executed by Rhino for condition checking and to do the actual transformations. I had around 15 transforms each with an average of 3 or 4 javascript based conditions and a 15 line block for the transform itself.

It takes about 100-300ms to compile all of that javascript (only short pieces of code) but reduced execution time for each transform from 4 or 5 secs to sub 100ms.

Bottom line:

  • It’s no where near 0.5secs to compile one script.
  • Subsequent runs when the classes are already loaded / JIT compiled are much faster.
  • Unsure about how Rhino works but the scripts are probably compiled anyway or are parsed the same.
  • The cost of caching an instance of a runtime generated class is minimal.[/quote]
    i didnt mean that it was literally 0.5 seconds, i just said 0.5 to indicate a short time

Read full topic

I recommend compiling the script if you want to use it multiple times, it is much faster.

actually, according to rhino docs, (actually im not 100% sure i read it a long time ago), rhino compiles all scripts before processing in newer versions

[/quote]

@zyle1992 wrote:

Okay, I got it working. Just one thing. How do I cal java objects as params in a function? Like let’s say I had this script:

function getName(player) {
    return player.getName();
}

How would I go about doing something like that, and calling that function from the application itself?

EDIT: Ok, I figured it out. Just using Invocable.invokeFunction with the scriptName and Object… args.

Mod can lock now.
